  1. Introduction                                                                          
                                                                                           
  Information Retrieval (IR) is the science of obtaining relevant information from large 
  unstructured collections in response to an information need expressed as a query [Manning
   et al., 2009, Ch. 1, p. 1]. With the explosion of digitally available text, the ability
  to efficiently locate relevant documents has become a fundamental requirement of modern
  computing systems.

  This report describes the design and implementation of an IR system built over a subset
  of Project Gutenberg — a corpus of over 70,000 public-domain books in plain-text format.
  The system is capable of indexing this large collection and responding to free-text
  queries by returning a ranked list of relevant documents.

  Retrieving relevant books from a collection of this scale presents three non-trivial
  challenges. First, vocabulary mismatch — users express their information need in words
  that may differ from those used in relevant documents [Manning et al., 2009, §2.1, p.
  19]. Second, scale — linearly scanning 70,000 documents for every query is
  computationally infeasible, requiring efficient index structures for fast lookup. Third,
  ranking quality — identifying documents that merely contain a query term is insufficient;
   results must be ordered by degree of relevance using principled scoring functions.

  To address these challenges, the system is built around the following pipeline:

  Raw Books + Metadata CSV
          ↓
    Preprocessing (normalisation, tokenisation, stop word removal)
          ↓
    Inverted Index (SQLite — body, title, author)
          ↓
    Query Parser (field-aware, supports structured and free-text queries)
          ↓
    ┌─────────────┬──────────────┬──────────┐
    │  Structured │     VSM      │   BM25   │
    │  (TF-based) │  (TF-IDF)   │  (Okapi) │
    └─────────────┴──────────────┴──────────┘
          ↓
    Ranked TSV Output (top 100 per query)

  Three retrieval models are implemented: a structured field-based search using term
  frequency (TF) scoring, a Vector Space Model (VSM) using TF-IDF cosine similarity, and
  BM25 (Okapi), a probabilistic ranking function. Each model is evaluated qualitatively
  against six predefined queries, and quantitatively using Precision@10, NDCG@10, and MRR.

  The remainder of this report is structured as follows: Section 2 describes the indexing
  pipeline, Section 3 details the three retrieval models, Section 4 presents the
  evaluation, and Section 5 concludes with findings and future directions.

  Reference: Manning, Raghavan & Schütze, Introduction to Information Retrieval, Cambridge
  University Press, 2009. Chapter 1 (p. 1–4), §2.1 (p. 19).

2. Indexing (Enhanced Version)                                                           
                  
  2.1 Document Collection

  The corpus originates from Project Gutenberg and initially comprises 75,294 plain-text
  .txt files. After filtering, the final indexed collection contains 70,694 documents,
  arrived at through the following process:

  75,294 total text files
     − 4,534 excluded: no matching metadata or has_text ≠ TRUE
               (audio books, image collections, non-textual formats)
  = 70,760 valid candidates
     −    66 excluded: empty content after boilerplate removal
               (65 empty stubs containing only Gutenberg policy text,
                1 corrupt/binary file)
  = 70,694 documents successfully indexed

  The 65 empty stub documents (IDs: 2291, 4461–4727 range) contained only the standard
  Project Gutenberg *** START OF *** / *** END OF *** markers with no body content between
  them. These were correctly identified and skipped by the indexer's empty-token check.

  ---
  2.2 Preprocessing Pipeline

  The preprocessing stage transforms raw textual data into a normalised token stream
  suitable for indexing. Following standard IR practice [Manning et al., 2009, Ch. 2], the
  following steps are applied:

  Step 1 — Boilerplate Removal.
  Every Project Gutenberg file begins with a legal header and ends with a licence footer,
  delimited by *** START OF THE PROJECT GUTENBERG EBOOK *** and *** END OF THE PROJECT
  GUTENBERG EBOOK ***. These sections are detected using regular expressions and stripped
  before any indexing occurs. Where these markers are absent, the first 100 lines are
  discarded as a conservative fallback. This prevents boilerplate phrases such as "Project
  Gutenberg" from artificially inflating term frequencies across the corpus, which is
  particularly important for query 5 ("Gutenberg").

  Step 2 — Unicode Normalisation (NFC).
  Text is normalised to Unicode NFC form using Python's unicodedata module. This
  canonicalises characters that may be represented differently at the byte level — for
  example, the German umlaut ö in Dornröschen — ensuring consistent matching regardless of
  encoding variant.
  "Token normalisation is the process of canonicalising tokens so that matches occur
  despite superficial differences in the character sequences of the tokens." [Manning et
  al., §2.2.3, p. 28]

  Step 3 — Lowercasing.
  All text is converted to lowercase so that Jabberwocky, jabberwocky, and JABBERWOCKY
  resolve to the same index entry.

  Step 4 — Tokenisation.
  The NLTK word_tokenize function splits text into individual tokens, correctly handling
  punctuation, contractions, and hyphenated terms.
  "The first step of determining the index units is tokenisation." [Manning et al., §2.2.1,
   p. 22]

  Step 5 — Punctuation Removal.
  Tokens containing no alphanumeric characters are discarded, removing standalone
  punctuation marks and symbols from the token stream.

  Step 6 — Stop Word Handling (field-dependent).

  This is a critical design decision. Stop words are treated differently depending on the
  field being indexed:

  - Title and author fields: Stop words are removed using NLTK's English stop word list.
  This reduces index size and improves precision for structured field queries, where
  function words such as "the" or "of" carry no discriminative information.
  "A stop list significantly reduces the number of postings that a system has to store."
  [Manning et al., §2.2.2, p. 27]
  - Body field: Stop words are intentionally retained. Stopwords were retained in the body
  index to preserve positional consistency required for phrase query processing. Although
  high-frequency terms have limited discriminative power, ranking models such as BM25
  inherently reduce their influence through inverse document frequency (IDF) weighting.
  Furthermore, removing stop words from the body index would make query 1 — "to be, or not
  to be" — return zero results, as every token in that query is a stop word.

  Step 7 — Stemming (optional).
  The Porter stemmer [Porter, 1980] is available via NLTK but disabled by default, as the
  Project Gutenberg corpus spans several centuries of English and many languages, where
  aggressive stemming risks conflating historically distinct word forms.
  "The most common algorithm for stemming English is Porter's algorithm." [Manning et al.,
  §2.2.4, p. 32]

  ---
  2.3 Index Architecture — Why Separate Field Indexes

  Three separate inverted indexes are maintained — body_index, title_index, and
  author_index — rather than a single unified index. This design was motivated by two
  requirements:

  1. The assignment explicitly requires search in structured data. Metadata fields (title,
  author) are structured and warrant different preprocessing (stop word removal) and
  different field weights in scoring. Maintaining separate indexes makes it straightforward
   to apply field-specific scoring weights (title = 3.0, author = 2.0, body = 1.0).
  2. Evaluation clarity. Separate indexes allow clear comparison of what structured search
  does well (precise author/title matching) versus what unstructured body search achieves
  (content-level relevance). For example, query 3 ("Philip K Dick") benefits directly from
  the author index, which correctly identifies books written by him rather than books that
  merely mention his name in the body text.

  ---
  2.4 Data Structures

  The inverted index is stored in a SQLite relational database (index.db) with the
  following schema:

  ┌──────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┐
  │    Table     │              Columns               │            Purpose             │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ body_index   │ term, doc_id, freq, positions      │ Full-text body terms with      │
  │              │ (BLOB)                             │ positions                      │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ title_index  │ term, doc_id, freq                 │ Title field terms              │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ author_index │ term, doc_id, freq                 │ Author field terms             │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ doc_lengths  │ doc_id, body_len, title_len,       │ Per-field document lengths     │
  │              │ author_len                         │                                │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ metadata     │ doc_id, title, author, language    │ Structured book metadata       │
  └──────────────┴────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┘

  Why SQLite?
  SQLite was chosen over an in-memory data structure for three reasons:

  1. Memory safety at scale. With approximately 70,000 books, holding the entire index in
  RAM simultaneously is infeasible. A Python dictionary can only be saved all at once — you
   cannot write half a dictionary to disk, clear RAM, and continue. SQLite allows writing
  one row at a time directly to disk as each document is processed. At any point in time,
  RAM holds only the current batch of 500 documents; the remainder is safely persisted on
  disk.
  2. Built-in to Python. No external dependencies are required — import sqlite3 is part of
  the Python standard library, satisfying the assignment's constraint against external IR
  libraries.
  3. Selective loading at query time. At search time, only the posting list for the
  specific query terms is loaded — not the entire index — making query processing fast and
  memory-efficient regardless of corpus size.

  Positional index for body:
  Word positions are stored as binary-serialised array.array('I') (unsigned 32-bit
  integers) in the positions BLOB column of body_index. This compact representation is
  approximately 7× smaller than storing positions as Python lists and enables phrase-level
  lookups. The positional index is essential for phrase search — verifying that query terms
   appear consecutively in a document requires knowing the exact position of each token.
  "In a positional index, for each term we store postings of the form docID: ⟨position1,
  position2, ...⟩" [Manning et al., §2.4.2, p. 42]

  ---
  2.5 Index Construction

  Documents are processed one at a time in batches of 500 (BATCH_SIZE = 500). Rather than
  loading all 70,000 books into memory before writing to disk, each document is read,
  preprocessed, and its rows accumulated in small in-memory buffers. Every 500 documents,
  the buffers are flushed to SQLite in a single transaction using executemany, then
  cleared. This bounds peak RAM usage to approximately 500 documents at any point during
  construction.

  SQLite is configured with:
  - WAL (Write-Ahead Logging): Allows concurrent reads during writes and improves
  bulk-insert throughput
  - NORMAL synchronous mode: Ensures data safety without the overhead of full fsync after
  every write
  - 64 MB page cache: Reduces disk I/O during the insertion phase

  B-tree term lookup indexes are created on the term column of each index table after all
  documents are inserted — not incrementally during insertion. Building an index over an
  already-populated table is significantly faster than maintaining it during bulk
  insertion, as the database can sort and construct the B-tree in a single optimised pass.
  "Index construction algorithms must deal with the constraint that memory is insufficient
  for large collections." [Manning et al., Ch. 4, p. 67]

  Document length tracking:
  During indexing, the token length of each field (body_len, title_len, author_len) is
  computed and stored in the doc_lengths table. The average document length (avgdl) for
  each field is derived from this table at query time. Both values are required by the BM25
   scoring formula for document length normalisation.

  References: Manning et al., §2.2.1 (p. 22), §2.2.2 (p. 27–28), §2.2.3 (p. 28–31), §2.2.4
  (p. 32–35), §2.4.2 (p. 41–44), Ch. 4 (p. 67–85). NLTK: Bird, Klein & Loper, Natural
  Language Processing with Python, O'Reilly, 2009, Ch. 3.

  3. Ranking

  3.1 Query Parser

  All three retrieval models share a common query parser that supports the following input
  formats:

  ┌───────────────────────┬──────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┐
  │     Input format      │       Example        │           Behaviour            │
  ├───────────────────────┼──────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Field-prefixed term   │ title:Hamlet         │ Searches title field only      │
  ├───────────────────────┼──────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Field-prefixed phrase │ author:"Philip Dick" │ Searches author field only     │
  ├───────────────────────┼──────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Plain term            │ Jabberwocky          │ Broadcasts to all three fields │
  ├───────────────────────┼──────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Plain phrase          │ "to be or not to be" │ Broadcasts to all three fields │
  └───────────────────────┴──────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────┘

  Unfielded query terms are broadcast to all three fields (title, author, body)
  simultaneously. This allows natural language queries such as "Philip K Dick" to match
  both author metadata and body text without requiring the user to specify field prefixes.
  Field weights are applied during scoring:

  ┌────────┬────────┐
  │ Field  │ Weight │
  ├────────┼────────┤
  │ Title  │ 3.0    │
  ├────────┼────────┤
  │ Author │ 2.0    │
  ├────────┼────────┤
  │ Body   │ 1.0    │
  └────────┴────────┘

  Title and author fields are given higher weight as an exact match in metadata is a
  stronger relevance signal than a body mention. This follows the weighted zone scoring
  framework described in Manning et al.:
  "In weighted zone scoring, we assign a weight to each zone of the document... the score
  of a document is the weighted sum of zone scores." [Manning et al., §6.1.1, p. 112]

  3.2 Structured Search (TF Scoring)

  The structured retrieval model scores documents using raw term frequency normalised by
  document length:

  Score(q, d) = Σ_field  field_weight × Σ_t  ( tf(t, d, field) / field_len(d) )

  This model serves as an interpretable baseline. It rewards documents in which query terms
   appear frequently relative to document length, but applies no IDF component — a term
  appearing in every document receives the same weight as a rare term.

  "The raw term frequency tf(t,d) of term t in document d is the number of times t occurs
  in d." [Manning et al., §6.2, p. 117]

  Advantage: Simple, fast, and interpretable — every score is directly proportional to how
  often the query term appears in the document.

  Disadvantage: Without IDF, common terms (e.g., "English") receive the same treatment as
  rare discriminative terms (e.g., "Jabberwocky"), reducing ranking precision for
  common-word queries.

  3.3 Vector Space Model (VSM)

  The VSM represents both documents and queries as vectors in a high-dimensional term
  space, ranking documents by their cosine similarity to the query vector [Manning et al.,
  §6.3, p. 120].

  TF weighting: Log-normalised TF is used to dampen the effect of high raw frequencies:
  tf_norm = log(1 + tf)
  "Log frequency weighting: wf(t,d) = 1 + log(tf(t,d)) if tf > 0." [Manning et al., §6.4.1,
   p. 127]

  IDF weighting: A smoothed IDF variant is used to avoid zero division and handle terms
  appearing in all documents:
  idf = log((N + 1) / (df + 1)) + 1

  Document score per field:
  score(t, d, field) = tf_norm × idf²
  The query term weight is treated as idf (assuming query term frequency = 1), and the
  document weight is tf_norm × idf, giving idf² in the dot product.

  Cosine normalisation: Scores are divided by √field_len to normalise for document length,
  preventing long documents from dominating results purely due to higher absolute term
  counts.

  "The cosine similarity between two vectors is their dot product divided by the product of
   their magnitudes." [Manning et al., §6.3, p. 121]

  Advantage: IDF down-weights common terms, improving precision for discriminative queries.
   Cosine normalisation fairly compares short poems to long novels.

  Disadvantage: The √field_len normalisation is an approximation of true cosine similarity
  and may not fully account for document length variation in a corpus as heterogeneous as
  Project Gutenberg.

  3.4 BM25 (Okapi BM25)

  BM25 is a probabilistic ranking function that extends TF-IDF with explicit document
  length normalisation and TF saturation [Manning et al., §11.4.3, p. 232]:

  BM25(t, d) = IDF(t) × (tf × (K1 + 1)) / (tf + K1 × (1 − B + B × dl/avgdl))

  IDF(t) = log((N − df + 0.5) / (df + 0.5) + 1)

  Parameters used: K1 = 1.5, B = 0.75. These values fall within the ranges recommended by
  Manning et al.:
  "A typical value of k1 is between 1.2 and 2, and b = 0.75." [Manning et al., §11.4.3, p.
  234]

  K1 controls TF saturation — as term frequency increases, the score approaches an
  asymptote of K1 + 1 = 2.5, preventing a single repeated term from dominating. B controls
  length normalisation — at B = 0.75, document length is strongly but not fully normalised
  against the corpus average.

  Advantage: Best-performing model in practice. TF saturation prevents term-spamming;
  length normalisation fairly compares short poems (e.g., Jabberwocky) to long novels. The
  IDF formula directly estimates term informativeness using the probabilistic framework.

  Disadvantage: Two free parameters (K1, B) require tuning; the default values used here
  were not optimised for this specific corpus.

  References: Manning et al., §6.1.1 (p. 112–115), §6.2 (p. 117–119), §6.3 (p. 120–126),
  §6.4.1 (p. 127), §11.4.3 (p. 232–234).

