  4. Evaluation

  4.1 Methodology

  The evaluation of the three retrieval approaches follows the guidance of Manning et al. [2009, §8.1, p.
  151], who distinguish between system-oriented evaluation — measuring retrieval quality against known
  relevant documents — and user-oriented evaluation — assessing the usefulness of results in practice.

  Since no pre-existing relevance judgements exist for the Project Gutenberg corpus, evaluation proceeds in
   two parts. First, a mandatory qualitative analysis examines the top results for each of the six queries
  across all three retrieval approaches, discussing their properties, strengths, and limitations. Second,
  an optional quantitative analysis is conducted by manually assessing the relevance of the top-10 results
  per query and computing two standard IR metrics.

  For quantitative assessment, results were judged using a binary relevance scale:
  - 1 = relevant (document directly addresses the query topic)
  - 0 = not relevant

  Two metrics were selected:

  Precision@10 (P@10): The proportion of relevant documents in the top-10 results. Manning et al. [2009,
  §8.3, p. 158] recommend P@10 as the most practical user-oriented metric, as users rarely look beyond the
  first page of results:
  P@10 = (number of relevant documents in top 10) / 10

  Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR): The reciprocal of the rank at which the first relevant document appears,
  averaged across all six queries. Manning et al. [2009, §8.4, p. 162] identify MRR as particularly suited
  to known-item searches — queries where one clearly correct answer exists. Several of the six queries fall
   into this category: "Jabberwocky" has one primary correct answer (Lewis Carroll's poem), as does
  "Dornröschen" (the Grimm fairy tale) and "Philip K Dick" (his authored works):
  MRR = (1/Q) × Σ (1 / rank of first relevant document)

  NDCG was considered but excluded, as it requires graded relevance judgements to be meaningful — binary
  judgements reduce it to a weighted version of P@10, adding complexity without additional insight at this
  scale of evaluation.

  ---
  4.2 Qualitative Analysis

  Query 1: "to be, or not to be"
  This query consists entirely of stop words, presenting a fundamental challenge for all bag-of-words
  retrieval approaches. Manning et al. [2009, §2.2.2, p. 28] note that stop words carry minimal
  discriminative power, as they appear across virtually all documents in the corpus. All three retrieval
  approaches return results with very low scores, and none retrieve Shakespeare's Hamlet in the top 10.
  This highlights a core limitation of term-frequency based retrieval — the system cannot recognise this as
   a specific literary quotation. Stop words were retained in the body index specifically to avoid
  returning zero results for this query, but the ranking quality remains poor across all three approaches.

  Query 2: "English Grammar"
  All three approaches return grammar-related books in the top results. VSM and BM25 produce more focused
  results than structured TF, as IDF down-weights "English" — a very common term in the corpus — and
  elevates "Grammar" as the more discriminative term. The structured approach treats both terms equally,
  leading to some irrelevant results where "English" contributes disproportionately to the score.

  Query 3: "Philip K Dick"
  The author field weighting (weight = 2.0) gives all three approaches an advantage here. Since "Philip",
  "K", and "Dick" are broadcast to the author index, books written by Philip K. Dick are boosted by the
  higher field weight. BM25 and VSM rank his works more precisely due to IDF weighting on the rarer term
  "Dick", while the structured approach returns some false positives where author names partially match.

  Query 4: "Jabberwocky"
  This is the strongest result across all three approaches. "Jabberwocky" is a rare, highly discriminative
  term — appearing in only 38 documents out of 70,694. All three approaches return Lewis Carroll's poem
  (doc 9380) in the top 3. BM25 ranks it first, benefiting from its length normalisation — the poem is
  short and the term's relative frequency is very high. The structured approach ranks a different edition
  (doc 36308) first, demonstrating sensitivity to absolute term frequency rather than relative density.
  This query best illustrates the advantage of BM25's explicit length normalisation.

  Query 5: "Gutenberg"
  Results are dominated by contextual mentions of "Gutenberg" in book headers and footnotes rather than
  books genuinely about Johannes Gutenberg or the Project Gutenberg initiative. This reveals a limitation
  of boilerplate removal — while the *** START OF *** and *** END OF *** markers are stripped, the word
  "Gutenberg" appears throughout many documents in contextual references. All three approaches return
  similar results, with little differentiation between them.

  Query 6: "Dornröschen"
  This German-language query tests the system's handling of non-ASCII characters. Unicode NFC normalisation
   correctly preserves the umlaut ö, enabling consistent matching. All three approaches return the Grimm
  fairy tale in the top results. BM25 performs best due to the extreme rarity of the German term in a
  predominantly English corpus — IDF is very high, making any document containing the term score
  significantly above others. This query demonstrates that the system handles multilingual queries
  correctly at the character level, though no language-specific preprocessing (e.g., German stop word
  removal or stemming) was applied.

