  5. Conclusions

  This report presented the design and implementation of an IR system over 70,694 Project
  Gutenberg books, incorporating an inverted index and three retrieval models: structured
  TF scoring, VSM, and BM25.

  What worked well: BM25 consistently produced the most relevant top-10 results across the
  six queries, owing to its explicit length normalisation and TF saturation. The
  field-weighted query parser successfully handled both structured (author:Carroll) and
  free-text queries by broadcasting unfielded terms across all three index fields. Unicode
  normalisation enabled correct handling of the German query Dornröschen.

  What did not work well: All three models struggled with query 1 ("to be, or not to be")
  due to its composition of exclusively stop words, which carry minimal discriminative
  weight in bag-of-words models. Additionally, query 5 ("Gutenberg") retrieved many
  documents due to contextual mentions rather than topical relevance, revealing a
  limitation of boilerplate removal.

  What would be changed: Future implementations could incorporate query expansion [Manning
  et al., §9.1] to address vocabulary mismatch, and phrase search to distinguish "to be or
  not to be" as a specific Shakespearean quotation from documents that merely contain these
   common words individually. BM25 parameters K1 and B could be tuned on a held-out query
  set to optimise for this specific corpus.

  Future extensions: Replacing bag-of-words representations with dense neural embeddings
  (e.g., BERT-based bi-encoders) would address vocabulary mismatch at a semantic level.
  Learning-to-rank approaches could combine signals from all three models to produce a
  single superior ranking.

